Text:
The last few weeks have been active despite (or because of) the lack of posting about.

Despite what I said previously, a working(ish) system has caused me to try to figure out some of the bigger conceptual pieces of the project.
Name: Travis

Text:
But I've come to a fork in the road.

Torgo's original conception was as a tool for me but also the JS creative coding community since that ecosystem can be a little fragmented

Just 𝚗𝚙𝚖 𝚒𝚗𝚜𝚝𝚊𝚕𝚕 𝚝𝚘𝚛𝚐𝚘, and you have a fiction generator to use in your project.
Name: Travis

Text: However, as I'm researching the NLP tools I can use to make Torgo work, the idea of having an npm package that can just be dropped in to an existing project is seeming unrealistic. Some of the libraries I want to use are just unavailable in Node.
Name: Travis

Text: Of course, I could port them, which would fulfill my original goal of serving the community. But do I really want to maintain multiple packages that draw from discrete projects? At the outset, I was worried about my ability to maintain a single package with any regularity.
Name: Travis

Text: So I'm faced with the choice of either abandoning my goal of making an easy-to-use community resource (which I always knew would be a major constraint) or ignoring some of the NLP developments that would make the project much more interesting conceptually.
Name: Travis

Text: Or I could just move the whole damn thing into Python and do both, since Python has native implementations of literally all the NLP libraries I want to use.
Name: Travis
